	<key>readme</key>
	<string>Browse, search, and open Git repositories from within Alfred.

GETTING STARTED

1. Click "Configure Workflow..." above
2. Under 🖥️ pick apps to open repos with
   (e.g. Default App = VS Code, Cmd App = iTerm)
3. Under the Search Directory sections, pick folders containing your Git repos
   (e.g. Search Directory 1 = ~/code, Depth = 2)
4. Type "repos" in Alfred and start searching!

USAGE

  repos &lt;query&gt;    Search your Git repositories
    ↩              Open in Default App
    ⌘↩             Open in Cmd App
    ⌥↩             Open in Alt App
    ^↩             Open in Ctrl App
    ⇧↩             Open in Shift App
    fn↩            Open in Fn App

  reposupdate      Force refresh the repo list
  reposhelp        Open help in your browser

CUSTOM REPO ICONS

Place a file named .alfred-repos-icon.png in the parent directory of a repo to give it a custom icon in results.

Example: if your repo is at ~/code/my-project, place the icon at ~/code/.alfred-repos-icon.png. All repos in ~/code/ will use that icon.

TIPS

- Browser apps (Chrome, Safari, Firefox, Arc, etc.) will open the repo's remote URL instead of the local folder.
- Set "Remote Name" to choose which git remote to use (default: origin).
- Use "Global Exclude Patterns" to skip directories like node_modules or .cache across all search directories.
- Use "reposupdate" after changing your search directories to refresh immediately.</string>
